   <titles>
      <title>Criteria for Convergence</title>
      <plain.title>Criteria for Convergence</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Recall the 
			<subordinate>
                     <hot>definition of convergence</hot>
                     <crossref>
                        <definition.ref definitionID="Def_SequenceConvergence"/>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Look up the definition of convergence of a sequence.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </crossref>
                  </subordinate>
			of a sequence <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr</latex>
                  </math>. When trying to decide whether such a sequence converges to a number, it may be quite tedious to rely on this definition only. Fortunately, there is a collection of tools which are very helpful in such situations. The purpose of this section is to develop the following criteria to detect convergence.</para.body>
            </para>
            <ul>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>A sequence which is increasing and bounded above converges to a number.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>A sequence which is decreasing and bounded below converges to a number.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Squeeze theorem for convergence to a number</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Rules for computing with convergent sequences</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ul>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                        href="MonotoneBoundedSeqConvergences_Thm.xml"/>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                        href="BolzanoWeierstrass_Thm.xml"/>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" href="NestedInterval_Thm.xml"/>
            <para>
               <para.body>At times it is possible to squeeze a complicated sequence between two sequences which converge to the same limit <math>
                     <latex>c</latex>
                  </math>. In this case the complicated sequence also converges to <math>
                     <latex>c</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" href="SqueezeTheorem_Thm.xml"/>
            <para>
               <para.body>We close this section with basic rules for computing with convergent sequences.</para.body>
            </para>
            <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" href="LimitRules_Thm.xml"/>
         </block.body>
      </block>
